WEBVTT

00:00:00.110 --> 00:00:06.840
Hello, my name is Jeff Colbett and I'm from Olathe, Kansas.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:16.160
I got started in investing in 1999 right before the big tech bubble and unfortunately I learned

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:24.160
buy and hold and don't fret about market price fluctuations before I learned the importance

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:28.720
of valuing a business and applying a margin of safety.

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:35.000
So, as Charlie said, I got my feet wet with huge failure right away.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.040
You're in the club.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:40.040
Thank you.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:43.120
I don't feel so bad now.

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:45.520
So that leads to my question.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:50.200
It seems like I've read all the Berkshire reports and all the reading I can do about

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:55.800
you too and and I thank you for these wonderful meetings but

00:00:55.056 --> 00:01:02.056
It seems like it boils down to some simple things, valuing a business and applying a margin of safety.

00:01:02.056 --> 00:01:10.056
So my question is, what do you recommend for an approach to getting better and better at valuing companies?

00:01:10.056 --> 00:01:14.816
That was a very, very good question.

00:01:14.816 --> 00:01:20.816
And in my own case, you know, I started out without doing anything about valuing companies.

00:01:20.816 --> 00:01:25.816
And Ben Graham taught me a way.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:31.520
to value a certain type of company

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:34.080
that would prove successful,

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:37.200
except the universe of those companies dried up.

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:41.960
But nevertheless, it was almost a guarantee against failure,

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:44.400
but it was not a guarantee that these things

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:46.320
would continue to be available.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:49.240
Charlie taught me a lot about the value

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:51.040
of a durable competitive advantage

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:54.120
and a really first class business.

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:54.960
What?

00:01:57.716 --> 00:02:01.916
Over time, I've learned more about various types

00:02:01.916 --> 00:02:04.396
of businesses, but you do be amazed how many businesses

00:02:04.396 --> 00:02:06.596
I don't feel that I understand well.

00:02:07.916 --> 00:02:12.516
The biggest thing is not how big your circle of competence is,

00:02:12.516 --> 00:02:14.036
but knowing where the perimeter is.

00:02:14.036 --> 00:02:20.476
If you don't have to be an expert on 90% of the businesses

00:02:20.476 --> 00:02:24.916
or 80% or 70 or 50, but you do have to know something

00:02:24.916 --> 00:02:26.956
about the ones that you actually put your money into.

00:02:26.956 --> 00:02:29.596
And if that's a very small part of the universe,

00:02:29.596 --> 00:02:31.636
that still is not a killer.

00:02:31.636 --> 00:02:32.476
And...

00:02:33.246 --> 00:02:36.006
I think if you think about what you would pay

00:02:36.006 --> 00:02:37.246
for a McDonald's stand,

00:02:37.246 --> 00:02:39.206
what you think you would pay for,

00:02:39.206 --> 00:02:40.346
you know, think about the businesses

00:02:40.346 --> 00:02:42.506
in your own hometown of, it's a laughing.

00:02:44.846 --> 00:02:47.486
Which would you like to buy into?

00:02:47.486 --> 00:02:49.686
Which do you think you could understand their economics?

00:02:49.686 --> 00:02:52.166
Which do you think will be around 10 or 20 years from now?

00:02:52.166 --> 00:02:55.046
Which do you think it would be very tough to compete with?

00:02:55.046 --> 00:02:57.606
Just keep asking yourself questions about businesses.

00:02:57.606 --> 00:03:00.126
Talk about with other people about them.

00:03:00.126 --> 00:03:02.726
You will extend your knowledge over time.

00:03:02.726 --> 00:03:05.806
and always remember that margin of safety.

00:03:05.806 --> 00:03:08.406
And I think you basically have the right attitude

00:03:08.406 --> 00:03:10.966
because you do, you recognize your limitations

00:03:10.966 --> 00:03:13.526
and that's enormously important in this business.

00:03:13.526 --> 00:03:15.326
You will find things to do.

00:03:15.326 --> 00:03:18.566
Six or seven years ago, maybe not that long.

00:03:18.566 --> 00:03:20.046
Yeah, six or seven years ago

00:03:20.046 --> 00:03:22.406
when I was looking at Korean stocks, for example,

00:03:22.406 --> 00:03:24.846
I never had any idea that Korean stocks

00:03:24.846 --> 00:03:26.966
would be something that I would be buying.

00:03:26.966 --> 00:03:29.686
But I looked over there and I could see

00:03:29.686 --> 00:03:31.326
that there were a number of businesses

00:03:31.326 --> 00:03:34.026
that met the margin of safety test,

00:03:34.026 --> 00:03:35.346
and there I diversified

00:03:35.346 --> 00:03:38.226
because I didn't know that much about any specific one,

00:03:38.226 --> 00:03:39.666
but I knew that the package of 20

00:03:39.666 --> 00:03:41.186
was going to work out very well,

00:03:41.186 --> 00:03:42.866
even if a crook might run one of them

00:03:42.866 --> 00:03:44.586
and a couple of might run into competition

00:03:44.586 --> 00:03:47.306
I didn't anticipate, because they were so cheap.

00:03:47.306 --> 00:03:49.626
And that was sort of the old Graham approach.

00:03:50.666 --> 00:03:52.906
You will find opportunities from time to time

00:03:52.906 --> 00:03:54.746
and the beauty of it is you don't have to find

00:03:54.746 --> 00:03:56.026
very many of them.

00:03:56.026 --> 00:03:59.926
Charlie?

00:03:59.926 --> 00:04:03.486
Well, obviously, if you want to get good at something,

00:04:03.486 --> 00:04:05.986
which is competitive.

00:04:05.986 --> 00:04:09.406
You have to think about it a lot and learn a lot

00:04:09.406 --> 00:04:12.546
and practice doing it a lot.

00:04:12.546 --> 00:04:17.446
And the way the world is constructed in this field,

00:04:17.446 --> 00:04:22.086
you have to keep learning because the world keeps changing

00:04:22.086 --> 00:04:26.006
and your competitors keep learning.

00:04:26.006 --> 00:04:30.286
So you just have to get up each morning

00:04:30.286 --> 00:04:36.286
and try and go to bed that night a little wiser

00:04:36.286 --> 00:04:37.586
than you were when you got up.

00:04:37.586 --> 00:04:40.406
And if you keep doing that for a long time

00:04:40.406 --> 00:04:44.626
and accumulate some experience good and bad

00:04:44.626 --> 00:04:47.946
as you try and master what you're trying to do,

00:04:49.686 --> 00:04:52.866
people who do that almost never fail utterly.

00:04:52.866 --> 00:04:54.446
They may have a bad period

00:04:55.706 --> 00:04:58.086
when luck goes against them or something,

00:04:58.086 --> 00:05:01.006
but very few people have ever failed with that.

00:05:02.206 --> 00:05:08.926
with that. If you have the right temperament, you may rise slowly, but you're sure to rise.

00:05:10.926 --> 00:05:13.566
Charlie, did you take any business courses in school?

00:05:14.126 --> 00:05:15.486
None. I took accounting.

00:05:17.006 --> 00:05:21.406
And when did you start valuing businesses, and how'd you go about it?

00:05:22.766 --> 00:05:28.926
When I was a little boy. I can remember I would come down to the Omaha Club, and there

00:05:28.926 --> 00:05:33.686
was an old gentleman who hit the Omaha Club about 10.30 every morning. He obviously did

00:05:33.686 --> 00:05:42.246
almost no work and yet was quite prosperous. He became your ideal. Well, but he made me

00:05:42.246 --> 00:05:48.286
very curious as a little boy. I said to my father, how in the hell does he do that?

00:05:48.286 --> 00:05:52.286
And he said, Charlie, he's in a business where he enjoys practically no competition.

00:05:52.286 --> 00:05:55.706
he gathers up and renders dead horses.

00:05:57.366 --> 00:05:59.726
That was an example of avoiding competition

00:05:59.726 --> 00:06:00.906
by one strategy.

00:06:03.586 --> 00:06:07.126
And if you keep asking questions like that of reality,

00:06:07.126 --> 00:06:09.666
starting at a young age, you gradually learn.

00:06:10.646 --> 00:06:12.606
And you were doing the same thing.

00:06:12.606 --> 00:06:16.166
Yeah, thankfully he went beyond his original

00:06:17.786 --> 00:06:19.126
insight there.

00:06:19.126 --> 00:06:28.226
I noticed, rather interesting, you take the rulers of the businesses, when I was a little

00:06:28.226 --> 00:06:35.576
boy, a lot of those businesses in Omaha, a lot of those businesses went broke, a lot

00:06:35.576 --> 00:06:41.936
of them sold out at modest prices under distress, and some of the people who rose like Keywit

00:06:41.936 --> 00:06:50.296
from small beginnings, nobody thought of as the great glories of that early time.

00:06:50.296 --> 00:06:53.216
And I think that's kind of the way life is.

00:06:53.216 --> 00:06:57.696
It's hard to get anywhere near the top, and it's hard to hold any possession once you've

00:06:57.696 --> 00:07:01.296
attained it.

00:07:01.296 --> 00:07:07.976
But I think you could predict the key what was likely to win.

00:07:07.976 --> 00:07:10.536
They cared more about doing it right.

00:07:10.536 --> 00:07:12.816
They cared more about avoiding trouble.

00:07:12.816 --> 00:07:15.016
They put more discipline on themselves.

00:07:15.016 --> 00:07:19.976
Well, if you knew the individual well, you would have bet, right?

00:07:19.976 --> 00:07:20.976
What?

00:07:20.976 --> 00:07:22.616
If you knew the individual, Pete himself would.

00:07:22.616 --> 00:07:28.576
I would not have bet on any of the people I knew who were already wealthy, but I would

00:07:28.576 --> 00:07:30.216
have bet on Pete Keywood.

00:07:30.216 --> 00:07:39.816
His sister taught me math, and no, half Dutch, half German, you know, this is a tough culture.

00:07:39.816 --> 00:07:46.096
There's your there you've just heard it folks half Dutch half German well but go

00:07:46.096 --> 00:07:51.536
out looking for him well the man that's recommending this is named Munger

00:07:51.536 --> 00:08:02.206
anyway the no I don't think it's that in but if you're I was just automatically

00:08:02.206 --> 00:08:07.246
doing that what was working what was failing why was it working why was it

00:08:07.246 --> 00:08:17.246
failing. If you have that temperament, you are gradually going to learn. And if you don't

00:08:17.246 --> 00:08:22.086
have that temperament, I can't help you.

00:08:22.086 --> 00:08:25.406
If you'd followed PQ at around for 10 years, you never would have seen him do anything

00:08:25.406 --> 00:08:26.406
dumb, right?

00:08:26.406 --> 00:08:34.016
Oh, yeah. And so it's avoiding the dumb thing. You really don't have to be brilliant, but

00:08:34.016 --> 00:08:40.916
You know, you have to avoid just sort of what almost seem the obvious mistakes.

00:08:40.916 --> 00:08:47.456
But I would say that you're on the right track back there in terms of having the basic fundamentals,

00:08:47.456 --> 00:08:51.736
knowing your limitations, but still seeking to learn more about various kinds of businesses.

00:08:51.736 --> 00:09:01.796
Charlie, I think when he practiced law, any client that came in, Charlie was thinking

00:09:01.796 --> 00:09:07.036
about that business is if he owned the place, and he probably generally probably knew more

00:09:07.036 --> 00:09:13.396
about the place than the guy that actually owned it, who was the client.

00:09:13.396 --> 00:09:18.236
But I remember talking to him, you know, 50 years ago, and he would start talking about

00:09:18.236 --> 00:09:21.676
caterpillar dealerships in Bakersfield or something of the sort.

00:09:21.676 --> 00:09:25.636
He was incapable of looking at a business without thinking about the fundamental economics

00:09:25.636 --> 00:09:29.226
of it.

00:09:29.226 --> 00:09:31.746
How'd that guy do with the caterpillar?

00:09:31.746 --> 00:09:40.656
Well, he sold it for a perfectly ridiculous price to a dumb oil company.

00:09:40.656 --> 00:09:43.416
It wasn't worth half what he got for it.

00:09:43.416 --> 00:09:44.416
But they had a concept.

00:09:44.416 --> 00:09:53.006
They had a concept in the strategy, and no doubt they had consultants.

00:09:53.006 --> 00:09:56.046
Becky?

00:09:56.046 --> 00:10:00.806
This question comes from Carson Mitchell in Aberdeen, South Dakota, who asks both of

00:10:00.806 --> 00:10:05.446
you, what business has had the best return on capital for Berkshire, and what business

00:10:05.446 --> 00:10:10.646
of any on earth has had the best return on capital and he adds P.S. I would have come

00:10:10.646 --> 00:10:14.966
by rail, but there are no seats in the grain rail cars.

00:10:14.966 --> 00:10:21.606
There's two ways of looking at it. If you talk about the capital necessary to run the

00:10:21.606 --> 00:10:27.086
business as opposed to what we might have paid for the business. I mean, if we buy

00:10:27.086 --> 00:10:31.446
a wonderful business, you could run the Coca-Cola company, assuming you had the bottling

00:10:31.446 --> 00:10:39.406
system separate. You can run it with no capital. Now, if you buy it for $100 billion, I mean,

00:10:39.406 --> 00:10:43.086
you can look at that as your capital or you can look at the basic capital. When we look

00:10:43.086 --> 00:10:48.006
at what's a good business, we're defining it in terms of the capital actually needed

00:10:48.006 --> 00:10:52.006
in the business. Whether it's a good investment for us depends on how much we pay for that

00:10:52.006 --> 00:11:00.806
in the end. There are a number of businesses that operate on negative capital. Carols

00:11:00.806 --> 00:11:09.486
with Fortune magazine. You know, any of the great magazines operate with negative capital.

00:11:09.486 --> 00:11:16.166
I mean, the subscribers pay in advance. There are no fixed assets to speak of, and the receivables

00:11:16.166 --> 00:11:23.366
are not that much. The inventory is nothing. So, a magazine business, I guess, is that

00:11:23.366 --> 00:11:31.726
magazine operates or sports illustrated operate with negative capital and particularly people

00:11:31.726 --> 00:11:35.006
make a lot of money.

00:11:35.006 --> 00:11:40.606
So there are certain businesses, well we had a company called Blue Chip Stamps where we

00:11:40.606 --> 00:11:49.366
got the float ahead of time and operated with really substantial negative capital.

00:11:49.366 --> 00:11:55.726
But there are a lot of great businesses that need very, very little capital.

00:11:55.726 --> 00:12:00.206
Apple doesn't need that much capital.

00:12:00.206 --> 00:12:04.966
The best ones, of course, are the ones that get very large, while needing no capital.

00:12:04.966 --> 00:12:08.486
Seize is a wonderful business, needs very little capital.

00:12:08.486 --> 00:12:14.526
But we can't get people eating 10 pounds of box chocolates every day.

00:12:14.526 --> 00:12:16.406
Except here.

00:12:16.406 --> 00:12:18.406
We want to.

00:12:18.406 --> 00:12:32.356
Generally, the great consumer businesses need relatively little capital.

00:12:32.356 --> 00:12:37.716
The businesses where people pay you in advance, magazines of Christians being a case, insurance

00:12:37.716 --> 00:12:46.736
being a case, you're using your customers' capital.

00:12:46.736 --> 00:12:50.456
We like those kind of businesses, but of course so does the rest of the world, so they can

00:12:50.456 --> 00:12:53.936
become very competitive in buying them.

00:12:53.936 --> 00:12:58.896
We have a business, for example, that's run wonderfully

00:12:58.896 --> 00:13:00.656
by Cathy Baron Tamra.

00:13:00.656 --> 00:13:01.696
It's called business wire.

00:13:01.696 --> 00:13:04.416
Business wire does not require a lot of capital.

00:13:04.416 --> 00:13:05.856
It has receivables and everything.

00:13:05.856 --> 00:13:08.176
But it is a service-type business.

00:13:08.176 --> 00:13:10.776
And many of the service-type businesses and consumer-type

00:13:10.776 --> 00:13:12.856
businesses require a little capital.

00:13:12.856 --> 00:13:15.616
And when they get to be successful,

00:13:15.616 --> 00:13:17.656
they can really be something.

00:13:17.656 --> 00:13:21.016
Charlie?

00:13:21.016 --> 00:13:25.456
I've got nothing to add, but at any rate,

00:13:25.456 --> 00:13:31.346
the formula never changes.

00:13:31.346 --> 00:13:33.866
If you could own one business in the world,

00:13:33.866 --> 00:13:43.166
what would it be, Charlie?

00:13:43.166 --> 00:13:45.006
I hope I already own them myself.

00:13:45.006 --> 00:13:49.206
Yeah, you and I got in trouble by addressing such a subject

00:13:49.206 --> 00:13:50.006
many decades ago.

00:13:50.006 --> 00:13:51.166
That's right.

00:13:51.166 --> 00:13:52.966
I don't think I'll come back to it.

00:13:52.966 --> 00:13:54.886
OK.

00:13:54.886 --> 00:13:56.406
Number 13.

00:13:56.406 --> 00:14:00.366
If you name some business that has incredible pricing power,

00:14:00.366 --> 00:14:02.446
You're talking about a business that's a monopoly,

00:14:02.446 --> 00:14:04.006
or a near-bought monopoly.

00:14:04.006 --> 00:14:04.846
Sure.

00:14:04.846 --> 00:14:08.326
And I don't think it's very smart for us to sit up here.

00:14:08.326 --> 00:14:10.246
Naming is our most admired business,

00:14:10.246 --> 00:14:12.926
is something that other people regard as a monopoly.

00:14:12.926 --> 00:14:13.766
OK.

00:14:13.766 --> 00:14:15.966
We'll move right along.

